g.text: Kim Kitsuragi: "But why? We work twelve-hour shifts. We get shot at, spat on..."
Rhetoric: Hah! Maybe there's a *reason* for that!
Kim Kitsuragi: "Hmh..." Just a hum. No reply.
Conceptualization: You've spoken. The wall will now silently repeat the message -- for a decade or so, until the sea air degrades the paint.
You: "But what do we work on? KEEPING EVERYTHING THE WAY IT IS."
You: Let the wall remain blank. For now. [Leave.]
You: "SOMETHING BEAUTIFUL IS GOING TO HAPPEN"
You: (Draw a 3,500 year old pictogram of a human being.)
You: "WHAT SHADOW LIES THERE, BENEATH THE BRIGHT GLEAM"
Kim Kitsuragi: The lieutenant looks at the wall in dismay:
Kim Kitsuragi: The lieutenant raises his eyebrows, then sighs.
Conceptualization: The wall towers over you with its indelible message.
Conceptualization: You've spoken. The wall will now silently repeat the message. For a decade or so, until the sea air degrades the paint, adding another layer of *detritus* to the city.

Kim Kitsuragi: "Very poetic." The lieutenant nods in appreciation -- it doesn't sound sincere. "Real poetry. Should we return to our murder investigation? I hear there's a really *bad* one we're supposed to solve."
You: "You're right, you're right. Is it too late to change it?"
Conceptualization: You've spoken. The wall will now silently repeat the message. For a decade or so, until the sea air degrades the paint, adding another layer of *detritus* to the city.
Conceptualization: The paintbrush in your hand is like a loaded revolver. What will it be, desperado? Quite a few things come to mind...
Conceptualization: Paintbrush -- check, heavy fuel oil -- check... Now the only thing left to do is paint the wall.
